Used_Cars Dataset Exploration¶

by Gbenga Olurankinse¶

Introduction¶

This document explore Used_Cars Dataset consist 7906 observations of used cars in some of the USA cities which were enlisted for sales with 18 features of the used cars. Some of the features are selling price, maximum power, transmission, year of purchase.

In [13]:
# function to orderly categorize column observations
def ordinal_cat(colm,val, order = False):
    """
    This function takes three parameters and returns the category datatype
    col : column to convert is datatype
    val : column observations, could be a list
    order : bool, default is False
    """
    order_year = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(categories = val, ordered = order)
    used_cars[colm] = used_cars[colm].astype(order_year)

col1_list = ['purchase_year', 'seats', 'owner']

unordered_list = [brand_list, region_list, state_list, fuel_list, seller_list, trans_list, city_list]
col2_list = ['brand', 'region', 'state', 'fuel', 'seller_type', 'transmission', 'city']
In [17]:
# loop to convert ordered lists to ordinal categorical variable
for col1 in range(len(col1_list)):
    ordinal_cat(col1_list[col1], ordered_list[col1], order=True)
    
#loop to  convert unordered lists to nominal categorical variable    
for col2 in range(len(col2_list)):
    ordinal_cat(col2_list[col2], unordered_list[col2])

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

the Used_Cars dataset has 7906 cars with 18 features. I changed the column names to lower case, renamed "name" to "brand", "state or province" to "state". Extract first word from "owner" column observations, then remove rows with "Test" observations. I moved on to convert "transmission", "seller_type", "fuel", and "region" columns to nominal categorical datatype. Also grouped years and asiigned it to a new variable "purchase_year" and convert it alongside with "seats", "owner" to ordinal categorical datatype.

Among the 18 features, 10 are categorical variables, 8 are numerical variables but after pre_wrangling the dataset, I now have 7901 rows and 16 columns of which 6 are numerical and 10 are categorical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

my interest is figuring out the feature(s) that best predict the selling price of the used cars in the gathered dataset

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

From the dataset, I expect max_power to have strong effect on the selling price (ideally, a car with better max_power should be expensive than cars with less max_power) though brand and other features like seats, mileage, km_driven, fuel, transmission, seller_type, owner, seats, and purchase_year are also expect to have effect on the selling_price but not as strong as max_power. I do not choose engine, region, state and city. mathematically, engine is proportional to max_power hence I expect both to positively correlate with each other. region, state and city are locations and variation in selling_price of used cars from one location is probably due to distance and considring cost of distance will equivalent offset selling price variation, moreover, there is no addional information like distance between cities/state/regions to investigate this.

# view the relationship using scatterplot
g = sb.PairGrid(data = used_cars, vars = numeric_var)

In [36]:
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)
plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])
sb.regplot(data=used_cars, x='max_power', y = used_cars['selling_price'].apply(log_trans),
           x_jitter=0.4, scatter_kws={"alpha":1/20}, fit_reg=False);
tick_locs = [3e4,1e5,3e5,1e6,3e6,1e7]
plt.yticks(log_trans(tick_locs), tick_locs);

# functions to plot violin and boxplot with Pairplot
def violingrid156(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ for creating boxp with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.violinplot(x=x, y=y, inner='quartile', color=base_color)
    plt.gcf().set_size_inches(15, 6)
    
def violingrid155(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ for creating boxp with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color=base_color)
    plt.gcf().set_size_inches(15, 5)
    
def cat_plot(df, cat_x, var = None, rotate = 0, boxgrid=None):

    count = 0

    for cat in cat_x:
        g = sb.PairGrid(data =df , y_vars = var, x_vars = cat, height = 3, aspect = 1.5)
        g.map(boxgrid)
        count+=1
        if cat == 'brand':
            plt.xticks(rotation=rotate)
    plt.show();
